Intro to R

STA9661

What is R?

If we go to the R web site to learn what R is all about, the first sentence is

R is a free software environment for statistical computing and graphics.

Brief History of R

  • Made from S:
    • developed as an internal statistical analysis environment by Bell lab in 1976.
    • S is from Statistics.
    • Subsequently sold as S-plus by a company called Insightful.

Intentional ambiguity

The ambiguity [of the S language] is real and goes to a key objective: we wanted users to be able to begin in an interactive environment, where they did not consciously think of themselves as programming. Then as their needs became clearer and their sophistication increased, they should be able to slide gradually into programming, when the language and system aspects would become more important. - John Chambers, one of the creators of the S language

Its all the things

  • Is it a programming language? An environment? A statistical package?
  • Eventually, it seems they settled on quantitative programming environment, or in other words, its all the things.

R!

  • R is a dialect of S.
    • R proved easy to adopt for previous users of S-PLUS and its free.
  • People already had tools for analyzing data
    • SAS, Stata, SPSS, Minitab, Microsoft Excel, etc.
  • But the commonly used data analysis packages had some key downsides:
    • The graphics were too quick and dirty and did not allow much control over the details; they plotted the data, but that was about it;
    • There was relatively little ability to build custom tools on top of what was available (although some capability was added to most packages later).

R solved these two key problems by providing an environment for statistical computing and graphics.

R for Data Analysis?

  • User/Analyst vs Developer/Programmer

The programming language and the ability to take fine control over all the details are things that would appeal to people who are developing new things (and youre seeing one of them now.).

  • R is, essentially, for making new things.

Download and install

  • Download R from CRAN website
  • Choose your system (Windows, Mac OS, Linux)
    • R itself is cross-platform but the instructor will use Mac OS and Linux.
    • Some details, especially the character set handling can be slightly different for Windows.
    • In most cases your system is likely 64 bit (if not, you may want to consider buying a new one).
  • Download RStudio from RStudio.
    • RStudio is an integrated development environment (IDE) that provides many nice features for using R.
  • Do it yourself (you may fumble at this stage but you should be able to do it. If not, seriously reconsider your major.).

Preamble

  • Whenever you see the gray box, it is a chunk of code.
  • The outcome of that chunk will follow with ##.
  • The code will be in different font family.

Character strings

Everything is not number in R.

ch <- "Hello World!"
ch
## [1] "Hello World!"
  • The object ch is a character (or string).
  • "" tells R that the object youre creating is a character (as opposed to numeric).
  • Be aware that data can be defined in various forms.
    • For example, consider a data associated with beer: Jirisan Moon Bear, IPA, 6.8%, Seoul.

Vector

  • c is to combine.
x <- c(1, 3, 5, 6) 
x
## [1] 1 3 5 6
x + 0.2
## [1] 1.2 3.2 5.2 6.2
  • Individual elements of a vector are accessed via [ bracket.
x[1]
## [1] 1
x[3]
## [1] 5
  • Be careful when you create an object; some may be reserved for other use. For example,
c

q

Help

  • functions do certain things, so they are more likely verbs rather than nouns.
  • Not surprisngly they are named after what they do, so you may be able to find it from your headbut even if you cant, you can use the nice feature from RStudio: type the first few letters and press tab.
  • You can also access the help file of a function using ?.
?c

Matrix

You can create a matrix using matrix.

mat_items <- c(1, 2, 3, 4)
matrix(mat_items, nrow=2)
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    3
## [2,]    2    4
matrix(mat_items, nrow=2, byrow=TRUE)
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    2
## [2,]    3    4

[ works similarly, but of course you can do more because it has two dimension (cols and rows).

A <- matrix(mat_items, nrow=2, byrow=TRUE)
A[1, 1]
## [1] 1
A[1, ]
## [1] 1 2
A[, 2]
## [1] 2 4

Notice that A is a matrix, A[1, ] is a (numeric) vector. (We will learn what numeric vector means later.)

Matrix can be used by combining vectors: by rows and columns.

vec_1 <- c(1, 3, 5)
vec_2 <- c(4, 6, 8)
# by row
rbind(vec_1, vec_2)
##       [,1] [,2] [,3]
## vec_1    1    3    5
## vec_2    4    6    8
# by cols
cbind(vec_1, vec_2)
##      vec_1 vec_2
## [1,]     1     4
## [2,]     3     6
## [3,]     5     8

What did we do?

  • We read the boys_shoes.csv data file into R using read.csv function.
  • function: a relationship or expression involving one or more variables.
    • Input - output relationship: you put something in it, it gives you something out.
    • For example, \(y = x^2\) is a function; if you feed \(x=2\), it returns \(y=4\).
    • So it maps your variables into a desired outcome.
    • it takes certain arguments as options; e.g., header=TRUE.
  • file.choose is another function, which tells read.csv that we will choose the file location in the diaglogue box.
  • Similarly, we defined boys by using boys <- read.csv(choose(), header=FALSE)

Working Directory

  • Working directory: A directory of a hierarchical file system associated with your work process.
  • Once you define the working directory, you can access files in the working directory without specifying its path.
  • getwd() returns current working directory.
  • setwd sets the working directory.
setwd("~/Dropbox/teaching/STA9661/2019F/lecture")
  • You may want to set up your keyboard shortcut for Set Working Directory to Current Documents Directory.

Path

  • on a Unix file system its / (Linux or OS X)
  • on a web serer its again /
  • on Windows its either \ (for the current disk) or D:\ (system-wide)
  • Relative paths are recommended in general, because you never know what environment in which your code will be run.
    • ./file.php (the file is in the current folder. The same as just file.php)
    • images/picture.jpg (the file is in the images folder that is in the current directory)
    • ../file.php (file is in the folder that is one level higher than the current directory)
    • ../../file.php (file is in the folder that is two levels higher than the current directory)

Naming objects

  • The name should represent what it contains choose the names that are concise and meaningful.
# Good
day_one

# Bad
first_day_of_the_month
djm1
  • Do not use likes of abc, mydata, temp, or dat1.
  • Technically you can use whatever you use, such as poop <- 3 but the names become very important when you are doing something complicated; and it is important to pick up good habits at the beginning.

Data frame

  • You may have noticed that boys is a special form of matrix (rows-and- columns structure).
  • A data frame is like a matrix, with a two-dimensional rows-and- columns structure.
    • However, it differs from a matrix in that each column may have a different mode.
    • For instance, one column may consist of numbers, and another column might have character strings.

Revisiting matrix

Lets quickly check what happens if we mix things up in matrix or in vector.

vec_mix <- c("A", 1, 3, "B")
vec_num <- c(1, 2, 3)
vec_ch <- c("A", "B", "C")
rbind(vec_num, vec_ch)
##         [,1] [,2] [,3]
## vec_num "1"  "2"  "3" 
## vec_ch  "A"  "B"  "C"

Q: What happened?

More on data frame

  • Data frame is most commonly added to your environment by importing an external data file, but you can also create one using data.frame.
data.frame(index = vec_num, ch = vec_ch)
##   index ch
## 1     1  A
## 2     2  B
## 3     3  C
  • In a tidy data frame, each column is usually a variable and each row is an observation.
  • If it is not the case, often the early stage of your data analysis should be spent on converting the data structure into a tidy format (often called tidying).
    • STA3034 is a course covering skills for this manuever.

Accessing the data from a data frame

  • Data frame is a special matrix, so its elements can be accessed using [.
boys[1, ]
##   boy matA sideA matB sideB
## 1   1 13.2     L   14     R
boys[1, 3]
## [1] L
## Levels: L R

Theres something special about data frames

  • Data frame also has an attribute called names (colnames); names of variables.
names(boys)
## [1] "boy"   "matA"  "sideA" "matB"  "sideB"
  • Its columns can be accesed by $ and the name of variable.
boys$matA
##  [1] 13.2  8.2 10.9 14.3 10.7  6.6  9.5 10.8  8.8 13.3

Data Frames

  • Data frame is similar to matrix, but each column may have different mode.
  • Data frame is a list.
  • data.frame() creates data frame objects by combining vectors and matrices.
    • stringsAsFactors = T (default): when data frames are created from character vectors, character vectors are converted into factor.
name <- c('Chuck','Grace','Alexandria')
age <- c(68, 43, 29)
male <- c(TRUE, FALSE, FALSE)
x <- data.frame(name, age, male, stringsAsFactors = F)
x
##         name age  male
## 1      Chuck  68  TRUE
## 2      Grace  43 FALSE
## 3 Alexandria  29 FALSE
  • str() shows structure of any R objects.
str(x)
## 'data.frame':    3 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ name: chr  "Chuck" "Grace" "Alexandria"
##  $ age : num  68 43 29
##  $ male: logi  TRUE FALSE FALSE
y <- data.frame(name, age, male)
str(y)
## 'data.frame':    3 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ name: Factor w/ 3 levels "Alexandria","Chuck",..: 2 3 1
##  $ age : num  68 43 29
##  $ male: logi  TRUE FALSE FALSE

Acessing Data frame

Access data frame like either list or matrix objects.

y[[2]]
## [1] 68 43 29
y[2:3]
##   age  male
## 1  68  TRUE
## 2  43 FALSE
## 3  29 FALSE
y$age
## [1] 68 43 29
y[,2]
## [1] 68 43 29

Operations of Data Frames

  • Operations of data frames are very similar to matrix objects.
  • Extracting a subset from data frame.
    • Indexing: If drop=F, data frame with one column \(\Rightarrow\) data frame. Otherwise, it is vector.
  • Filtering.
  • subset(): Exclude obs. with NA.
x <- data.frame(x1 = c(6, 3, 6, 3, 8), x2 = 1:5, x3 = 7:11)
x
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 2  3  2  8
## 3  6  3  9
## 4  3  4 10
## 5  8  5 11
x[x$x1 >= 5, ]
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 3  6  3  9
## 5  8  5 11
x[x[,1] >= 5, ]
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 3  6  3  9
## 5  8  5 11
x <- data.frame(x1 = c(6, 3, NA, 3, 8), x2 = 1:5, x3 = 7:11)
x
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 2  3  2  8
## 3 NA  3  9
## 4  3  4 10
## 5  8  5 11
x[x$x1 >=5,]
##    x1 x2 x3
## 1   6  1  7
## NA NA NA NA
## 5   8  5 11
subset(x, x1 >= 5)
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 5  8  5 11

Merging Data Frames

  • merge(): Combine two data frames according to the values of common variable.
d1 <- data.frame(name = c('Rodgers', 'Choi', 'Field'), age = c(32, 27, 49), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
d2 <- data.frame(Sex = c("M", "F", "M"), name = c('Luck', 'Field', 'Gene'), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
merge(d1, d2, by = 'name')
##    name age Sex
## 1 Field  49   F
merge(d1, d2, by='name', all = T)
##      name age  Sex
## 1    Choi  27 <NA>
## 2   Field  49    F
## 3    Gene  NA    M
## 4    Luck  NA    M
## 5 Rodgers  32 <NA>

as.data.frame() converts objects into data frames.

as.data.frame(x)
##   x1 x2 x3
## 1  6  1  7
## 2  3  2  8
## 3 NA  3  9
## 4  3  4 10
## 5  8  5 11
a <- matrix(0,2,2)
x <- as.data.frame(a)
is.data.frame(x)
## [1] TRUE
